        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(ollama): release stream reader lock to prevent resource leak",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`extensions/ollama/src/stream.ts:1463` acquires a `ReadableStream` reader via `response.body?.getReader()` but does not call `reader.releaseLock()` in the finally block. If the stream processing throws, the reader lock is leaked — the underlying stream remains locked and cannot be reused or garbage-collected.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `extensions/ollama/src/stream.ts`: add `reader.releaseLock()` (wrapped in try/catch) before `await release()` in the finally block\n\nThis matches the defensive lock-release pattern used elsewhere in the codebase where stream readers are acquired and must be released regardless of success or failure.\n\nLabel: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Code path analysis\n\nThe affected function `createRawOllamaStreamFn`:\n1. Acquires `reader = response.body?.getReader()` \n2. Enters a `while (true)` loop reading chunks\n3. Has a `finally` block that calls `await release()` but did NOT call `reader.releaseLock()`\n\nIf any iteration of the read loop throws (e.g., parse error, abort), the finally block runs `release()` but the reader lock remains held. Adding `reader.releaseLock()` in the same defensive try/catch pattern ensures the lock is released.\n\n### Risk assessment\n\nThe change adds 3 lines (`try { reader.releaseLock(); } catch {}`) inside an existing finally block. The try/catch wrap ensures that even if `releaseLock()` itself throws (e.g., reader already released), the `await release()` path still executes.",
